th questions of tradition, memory, trauma, madness, atrocity, and faith. The Struggle for Understanding examines Wiesel's literary, religious, and cultural roots and the indelible impact of the Holocaust on his storytelling. Grouped in sections on Hasidic origins, the role of the Other, theology and tradition, and later works, the chapters cover the entire span of Wiesel's career. Books analyzed include the novels Dawn, The Forgotten, The Gates of the Forest, The Town Beyond the Wall, The Testament, The Time of the Uprooted, The Sonderberg Case, and Hostage, as well as his memoir, Night. What emerges is a portrait of Wiesel's work in its full literary richness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aHistory : Holocaust Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aBo, Federico Dal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnglander, Yakir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorowitz, Rosemary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeren-Kratz, Menachem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMargolis, Peppy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayse, Ariel Evan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMihӑilescu, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMueller, Mary Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNesfield, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNesfield, Victoria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 a